  <div class="head">
      <div class="head-container">
        <h1>Clinical Stages of Alzheimer’s</h1>
      </div>
      <img src="https://www.alzinfo.org/wp-content/themes/alzinfo-new-site-2020/images/page-bkgrd.jpg?v=1597679997033" srcset="https://www.alzinfo.org/wp-content/themes/alzinfo-new-site-2020/images/page-bkgrd-p-1080.jpeg?v=1597679997033, https://www.alzinfo.org/wp-content/themes/alzinfo-new-site-2020/images/page-bkgrd-p-1600.jpeg?v=1597679997033, https://www.alzinfo.org/wp-content/themes/alzinfo-new-site-2020/images/page-bkgrd.jpg?v=1597679997033" sizes="100vw"  alt="" class="page-parallax">
  </div>
  <div class="background">
    <div class="background-top">
      <div class="background-top-left">
        <h1>7 Stages of Alzheimer’s</h1>
        <p>The seven Clinical Stages of <a href="https://www.youtube.com/embed/7_kO6c2NfmE?controls=0">Alzheimer’s disease</a>, also known as the Global Deterioration Scale (GDS), was developed by <a href="https://www.alzinfo.org/about/bios/dr-barry-reisberg/">Dr. Barry Reisberg</a>, Director of the Fisher Alzheimer’s Disease Education and Research program at NYU Grossman School of Medicine. This guideline is used by professionals and caregivers around the world to identify at what stage of the disease a person is in. Stages 1-3 are the pre-dementia stages; stages 4-7 are the dementia stages. Stage 5 is the point where a person can no longer live without assistance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="background-top-right">
        <img width="400" height="500" src="https://www.alzinfo.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Reisberg.jpg" class="vc_single_image-img attachment-large" alt="" decoding="async" title="Reisberg" srcset="https://www.alzinfo.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Reisberg.jpg 400w, https://www.alzinfo.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Reisberg-240x300.jpg 240w" sizes="(max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px">
      </div>
    </div>
   
    <div class="background-link">
